STEP 1: Update and Upgrade the System

Open the terminal and run the following command:

sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

Explanation:
This command updates the package list and upgrades all installed packages to the latest version.

STEP 2: Install Required Dependencies

Run the following command:

sudo apt install -y python3-pip python3-dev libffi-dev libssl-dev

Explanation:
These packages are required for Ansible to run properly. They provide Python tools and security libraries needed by Ansible.

STEP 3: Install Ansible

Run the following command:

sudo apt install -y ansible

Explanation:
This installs the Ansible automation tool from the system repository.

STEP 4: Verify Ansible Installation

Run the command:

ansible --version

Explanation:
This command displays the installed version of Ansible and confirms that the installation was successful.

STEP 5: Create a YAML Playbook File

Create a file using the following command:

nano install_nginx.yml

Add the following YAML code inside the file:

- name: Install and Start NGINX
  hosts: localhost
  become: yes

  tasks:
    - name: Install NGINX
      apt:
        name: nginx
        state: present

    - name: Start Nginx service
      service:
        name: nginx
        state: started

    - name: Create a file
      file: 
        path: /home/kali/demo.txt
        state: touch


Save the file and exit the editor.

Explanation:
This playbook performs three tasks:

Installs the NGINX web server.

Starts the NGINX service.

Creates a file named demo.txt in the home directory.

STEP 6: Run the YAML Playbook

Run the playbook using the following command:

ansible-playbook install_nginx.yml

Explanation:
This command executes the YAML playbook and performs all tasks defined inside it.

STEP 7: Verify the File Creation

Run the following command:

ls -l ~/demo.txt

Explanation:
This command checks whether the file demo.txt has been created successfully.

STEP 8: Remove the Default Index File

Run the command:

sudo rm /var/www/html/index.html

Explanation:
This removes the default NGINX web page so that a custom page can be served.

STEP 9: Check the Web Server

Open a browser and go to:

http://localhost
